Cell.Text: [S] G|Even though the Phial was damaged, I still think your efforts deserve reward. | Now, if you'll pardon me, I'm going to tend to Nurelion. I can make his final days a bit less painful.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusRepairInstructionsCallPlayerTopic: I was happy to help.

Cell.Text: [S] G|Thank the gods. I'll get to work on the Phial straight away.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusRepairingPhialBranchTopic: I have the materials you requested.

Cell.Text: He is gone. | But thanks to you, he died knowing his life's work was not in vain.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusAfterNurelionsDeathTopic: What happened to Nurelion?

Cell.Text: As am I. | You acted very nobly in helping my master realize his life's work. Thank you for that. | As for myself, I've always been content to simply be an alchemist. | I fear keeping the Phial would just remind me of Nurelion's obsession, and how it consumed him. | Here, keep it. You are as much a part of its legend now as Curalmil was. I hope it brings you the happiness that my master desired.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusNurelionIsDead: I'm sorry to hear that.

Cell.Text: On top of the Throat of the World is a patch of snow that's never melted. | They say the Greybeards taught it to ignore the sun, and heat simply washes over it. | The original Phial was made from this snow. We'll only need a small bit for the repairs.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusAboutSnowTopic: Tell me about the Unmelting Snow.

Cell.Text: The ivory produced by those beasts is as hard as iron. But the giants have found ways to make it yield. | They're able to grind it down so fine that it can be infused into the lattice of packed snow. | The finished material has the delicate nature of fresh powder snow, but the strength of the hardest steel.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusAboutPowderTopic: Tell me about the Mammoth Tusk Powder.

Cell.Text: The final tempering of the Phial was performed with a type of old magic that's been lost since the Dragon War. | The nearest modern incarnation of it is the strange rituals practiced by the Forsworn. | With the heart of one of their Briar Warriors, I can lock the Phial's magic into its physical form. | It's difficult to explain to the layman -- forgive me if I begin waxing alchemic.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusAboutBriarHeartTopic: Tell me about the Briar Heart.

Cell.Text: Good to hear. You can be a difficult man to find. Thankfully those couriers are tenacious.
Good to hear. You can be a difficult woman to find. Thankfully those couriers are tenacious.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusSendsYouOffTopic: I received your letter.

Cell.Text: [S] I have some thoughts. There are three crucial elements. Some may be easier to find than others. | On the top of the Throat of the World is a patch of Unmelting Snow. No heat can touch it. | Then we need the tusk of a mammoth, ground to a fine powder as only the giants know how. | The final step is tricky. It requires the briar heart from a Forsworn of the Reach. | If you can bring me these materials, the Phial can again be made whole.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusCanRepair: You think you know how to repair the Phial?

Cell.Text: I want to thank you for your help. I know my master can be a bit short at times.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusHeyThanksDude

Cell.Text: Here, you should have this.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusAllGood: I was happy to help.

Cell.Text: Oh, I'm sorry about that.

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusCheapskate: Nurelion only gave me five septims.

Cell.Text: <<Shared>> Now, how would you like me to align the Phial's properties?

Node.Caption: MS12QuintusAlignTopic1

Cell.Text: <<Shared>> I'm not as skilled as Curalmil, so I'm afraid it will only ever refill with one type of liquid.
